# 55_actions_transform_bool_smoke — Tier 2 m5 Transforms + Booleans
# sweep (s255). Validates the five wrap-now verbs migrated from raw
# `add_action` to `add_scripted_action`:
#   - Transforms: flip-horizontal / flip-vertical
#   - Booleans:   bool-union / bool-subtract / bool-intersect
#
# Sibling smoke to 52 / 53 / 54, same conservative-shape posture:
# verb-presence + invocation-no-throw + refusal coverage.
#
# **Why conservative.** No scriptable observables exist today for flip
# (selection transform — no `objects` bounding-box / transform-matrix
# property) or for boolean ops (their effect is the canvas mutating
# from N selected paths to 1 fused path; `objects` doesn't expose
# selection-count). Trace channel: invocations land cleanly. Visual
# channel: Scott confirms the menu items still perform the operations
# identically.
#
# ── Boolean ops and the disabled-action quirk ─────────────────────────────
#
# bool-union / bool-subtract / bool-intersect are stored as MainWindow
# members (`m_act_bool_*`) and managed by `update_bool_actions_sensitive()`
# — the s122 m2 sensitivity pump that disables them unless exactly 2
# closed paths are selected. **The disabled flag is a UI gate, not a
# programmatic gate.** `Gio::SimpleAction::activate()` (which is what
# the wrapper calls) fires the signal regardless of enabled state.
#
# So a script `win bool-union` with an empty / wrong selection will:
#   - Trace channel: still `ok`. The wrapper isn't refusing.
#   - Canvas channel: `m_canvas.boolean_op()` runs with bad input and
#                     does whatever it does on bad input (likely a no-op
#                     or an early-return guard; not a crash).
#   - Visual channel: nothing changes (no selection of 2 closed paths
#                     to fuse).
#
# This is NOT a wrapper-side bug. The wrapper is structurally invariant
# at the dispatch layer (white-box reads, black-box writes, per
# Scriptable.hpp). Selection-validity is canvas-side business. If a
# future `selection` Scriptable exposes `count` / `closed_count`,
# scripts can self-gate. Today, scripts trust the underlying handler.
#
# **For the smoke:** the three boolean ops fire `ok` regardless of
# selection state. The trace channel pass. Scott's visual channel is
# the second axis and is most legible if the smoke is run with exactly
# 2 closed paths selected — then bool-union fuses them, and the
# subsequent bool-subtract / bool-intersect operate on whatever
# the fuse left selected (which may not satisfy exactly-2 anymore;
# net effect is a small visual surprise but no crash).
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Eight observables across the wrapper-side surface:
#
#   Phase 1: `list` — confirm `win` is still registered.
#
#   Phases 2-3: flip verbs invoked once each. Visual: selection
#            mirrors across X (flip-horizontal) or Y (flip-vertical).
#            Two flips on the same axis cancel out.
#
#   Phases 4-6: boolean verbs invoked once each. See the disabled-
#            action note above; trace channel passes regardless of
#            selection state.
#
#   Phases 7-8: refusal coverage. Unknown-verb + extra-argument
#            refusals.
#
# ── Caller context ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Runs through ScripterWindow's listener, m_context = RunContext::Scripter.
# All five m5-batch verbs declare Scripter | TestRunner. Macro is OUT.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Mutations to canvas state:
#
#   - `win flip-horizontal` — selection mirrors across X.
#   - `win flip-vertical`   — selection mirrors across Y.
#                             Net of phases 2+3: selection rotated 180°
#                             (flip-X then flip-Y = rotate-180 around
#                             selection center).
#   - `win bool-union`      — if exactly 2 closed paths selected,
#                             fuses them. Otherwise no-op (canvas-side).
#   - `win bool-subtract`   — if the post-union selection is a valid
#                             2-path config (probably not — bool-union
#                             leaves 1 path selected), no-op.
#   - `win bool-intersect`  — same as bool-subtract.
#
# After the smoke runs:
#   - If pre-run state was 2 closed paths selected: post-run is 1 fused
#     path, rotated 180° relative to the original midpoint between them.
#   - Otherwise: just the 180° rotation from the two flips, no boolean
#     effect. Scott may want a few ⌘Z presses to restore.
#
# Safe to run repeatedly. Not idempotent in the multi-path case.
#
# ── Precondition reminders ────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke assumes:
#   1. Curvz is running with at least one project + one document open.
#   2. Recommended for visual-channel legibility: select exactly 2 closed
#      paths (e.g., draw two rectangles with the rect tool, select both)
#      so phase 4's bool-union has a visible effect. The trace channel
#      passes either way.

#[sub] === Phase 1: registry sanity-check — `win` is still registered ===

#[sub] Re-confirms m2/m3/m4 plumbing didn't regress.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: flip-horizontal verb is addressable ===

#[sub] First m5-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.flip_selection(true);
#[sub] visual: selection mirrors across vertical axis.

win flip-horizontal

#[sub] === Phase 3: flip-vertical verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Second m5-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.flip_selection(false);
#[sub] visual: selection mirrors across horizontal axis. Combined
#[sub] with phase 2 = 180° rotation around selection center.

win flip-vertical

#[sub] === Phase 4: bool-union verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Third m5-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.boolean_op(Union); visual:
#[sub] if exactly 2 closed paths selected, they fuse into one. The
#[sub] wrapper fires regardless of selection state (see disabled-action
#[sub] note in the smoke preamble).

win bool-union

#[sub] === Phase 5: bool-subtract verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Fourth m5-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.boolean_op(Subtract);
#[sub] visual: A minus B if exactly 2 closed paths selected. After
#[sub] phase 4's union, selection is likely the single fused path, so
#[sub] this is a no-op at the canvas layer. Wrapper still fires `ok`.

win bool-subtract

#[sub] === Phase 6: bool-intersect verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Fifth and final m5-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.boolean_op(Intersect);
#[sub] same disabled-action-fires-anyway shape as phases 4/5.

win bool-intersect

#[sub] === Phase 7: unknown-verb refusal ===

#[sub] Same refusal smoke as 52/53/54.

win quit

#[sub] === Phase 8: extra-argument refusal ===

#[sub] Use one of the new m5 verbs for refusal coverage.

win flip-horizontal "argument"

